meanings":["German (mainly <b>Günter</b>) and English: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Gunter</i> (Old French <i>Gontier</i>), composed of the elements <i>gund</i> ‘battle’ + <i>hari</i>, <i>heri</i> ‘army’. Compare   Guenter  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gunterman","meanings":["Americanized form of German (North Rhine-Westphalia) <b>Guntermann</b>: elaborated form of   Gunter  . Compare   Counterman  ."]},{"name":"Gonter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Bernhardt, Frieda.  Jewish Avrohom.","German: from a variant of the personal name <i>Günter</i> (see   Gunter  ) or an altered form of   Ganter  .","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): occupational name, a Yiddishized form of Ukrainian <i>gontar</i> ‘shingle maker’."]},{"name":"Gonthier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Henri, Alexandre, Andre, Chantale, Denys, Gilles, Monique, Normand, Piere, Renald.","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Gundhari</i>, composed of the elements <i>gund</i> ‘battle’ + <i>hari</i>, <i>heri</i> ‘army’ (see   Gunter  ). Compare   Gauthier   2.","History: Bernard Gonthier from Paris, France, married Marguerite Paquet in Quebec City, QC, in 1676."]},{"name":"Gunsch","meanings":["German (<b>Günsch</b>): from a short form of the personal name <i>Günther</i> (see   Gunter  )."]},{"name":"Gunther","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Gerhard, Fritz, Otto, Rudi, Alphons, Arno, Bernd, Dieter, Ehrhardt, Erwin, Gunther.","German (mainly <b>Günther</b>): variant of   Gunter  ."]},{"name":"Goenner","meanings":["North German (<b>Gönner</b>): from the personal name <i>Gönner</i>, a variant of   Gunter  , composed of the elements <i>gund</i> ‘battle’ + <i>hari</i>, <i>heri</i> ‘army’. Compare   Gonnerman  ."]},{"name":"Gunder","meanings":["German (also <b>Günder</b>): variant of   Gunter  ."]},{"name":"Guenter","meanings":["German (mainly <b>Günter</b>): see   Gunter  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":15,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Gunter was born about 1440, in Sussex, England. She had at least 1 son with Richard Bowyer of Petworth. She died in 1498, at the age of 59."},"et":{"about 1440–1498":"umbes 1440–1498","1435–1506":"1435–1506","1465–1528":"1465–1528","1440–1498":"1440–1498","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1498":"1498","1465":"1465","1440":"1440","about 1440":"umbes 1440","1528":"1528","1506":"1506","abt 1465":"umbes 1465","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England"},"fi":{"about 1440–1498":"noin 1440–1498","1435–1506":"1435–1506","1465–1528":"1465–1528","1440–1498":"1440–1498","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1498":"1498","1465":"1465","1440":"1440","about 1440":"noin 1440","1528":"1528","1506":"1506","abt 1465":"noin 1465","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England"},"fr":{"about 1440–1498":"environ 1440–1498","1435–1506":"1435–1506","1465–1528":"1465–1528","1440–1498":"1440–1498","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1498":"1498","1465":"1465","1440":"1440","about 1440":"environ 1440","1528":"1528","1506":"1506","abt 1465":"environ 1465","Sussex, England":"Sussex, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Joan Gunter est née environ 1440, à Sussex, Angleterre. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Richard Bowyer of Petworth. Elle est décédée en 1498, à l’âge de 59 ans."},"de":{"about 1440–1498":"um 1440–1498","1435–1506":"1435–1506","1465–1528":"1465–1528","1440–1498":"1440–1498","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1498":"1498","1465":"1465","1440":"1440","about 1440":"um 1440","1528":"1528","1506":"1506","abt 1465":"um 1465","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","lifeSummary":"Joan Gunter wurde um 1440 in Sussex, England geboren. Sie hatte mit Richard Bowyer of Petworth mindestens 1 Sohn. Sie starb 1498 im Alter von 59 Jahren."},"ht":{"about 1440–1498":"about 1440–1498","1435–1506":"1435–1506","1465–1528":"1465–1528","1440–1498":"1